# ScentTwin - Cursor AI Rules

You are an expert Angular developer building ScentTwin, a premium fragrance recommendation PWA with a bold purple/black aesthetic.

## Project Context

- **Project**: ScentTwin - Personalized fragrance recommendation app
- **Tech Stack**: Angular 18, TypeScript, SCSS, Supabase, Angular Material
- **Design System**: Purple (#6b21a8) primary, Gold (#f59e0b) accent, Pure black (#000000) background
- **Priority**: Eye-catching, premium UI that captures user attention immediately

## Code Standards

### Component Architecture
- **ALWAYS** generate components with separate `.ts`, `.html`, and `.scss` files
- **NEVER** use inline templates or inline styles
- Use standalone components by default (`standalone: true`)
- Follow strict naming convention: `component-name.component.ts/html/scss`
- Organize components in dedicated folders under `features/[module]/components/[component-name]/`
- Every component must include proper TypeScript types and interfaces

### File Structure
features/
├── [module-name]/
│ ├── components/
│ │ ├── [component-name]/
│ │ │ ├── [component-name].component.ts
│ │ │ ├── [component-name].component.html
│ │ │ ├── [component-name].component.scss
│ │ │ └── [component-name].component.spec.ts
│ ├── services/
│ ├── [module-name].module.ts
│ └── [module-name].routes.ts

text

### TypeScript Rules
- Use **strict mode** - never use `any` type
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object definitions
- Use explicit return types for all functions
- Use `inject()` function for dependency injection in modern components
- Implement proper error handling with try/catch and RxJS error operators
- Use RxJS operators (`map`, `filter`, `switchMap`, `catchError`) properly
- Always unsubscribe from observables using `takeUntil` or async pipe

### Angular Best Practices
- Use **OnPush** change detection strategy where possible
- Implement **lazy loading** for all feature modules
- Use **Angular Signals** for reactive local state when appropriate
- Prefer **async pipe** over manual subscription
- Use **trackBy** functions with `*ngFor` for performance
- Implement route guards for authentication and navigation
- Follow Angular's official style guide

### Styling Guidelines
- **ALWAYS** use the design system from `src/assets/styles/`
- Import variables: `@import 'src/assets/styles/variables';`
- Use utility classes: `.glass-card`, `.btn-primary`, `.btn-accent`, `.gradient-text`
- Apply smooth transitions: `transition: all 0.3s ease;`
- Include hover effects with `transform: translateY(-2px);`
- Use CSS Grid and Flexbox for layouts
- Mobile-first responsive design with breakpoints
- Dark theme by default - ensure sufficient contrast
- Use SCSS nesting and variables for maintainability

### Design System Colors
$color-primary: #6b21a8; // Deep purple
$color-primary-light: #a855f7; // Light purple
$color-accent: #f59e0b; // Bright gold
$color-accent-dark: #d97706; // Dark gold
$color-black: #000000; // Pure black
$color-white: #ffffff; // White

text

### UI/UX Requirements
- Every interactive element must have hover and active states
- Use glass-morphism effects for cards and containers
- Include smooth animations and transitions (0.3s ease)
- Add loading states for async operations
- Implement proper error states with user-friendly messages
- Use gradient backgrounds for buttons and headings
- Apply box-shadows for depth and visual hierarchy
- Ensure accessibility (ARIA labels, keyboard navigation, color contrast)

### Supabase Integration
- Always use `SupabaseService` singleton for database operations
- Implement Row Level Security (RLS) policies for all tables
- Use RxJS observables for real-time subscriptions
- Handle authentication state changes properly
- Include error handling for all Supabase operations
- Use environment variables for Supabase credentials

### Performance Optimization
- Implement lazy loading for routes and components
- Use `ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush` where appropriate
- Optimize images (WebP format, lazy loading)
- Implement virtual scrolling for long lists
- Use Angular's built-in performance tools
- Minimize bundle size with tree-shaking

### Security Best Practices
- Sanitize user inputs using Angular's `DomSanitizer`
- Implement CSRF protection
- Use HTTPS only in production
- Validate all user inputs on frontend and backend
- Implement rate limiting for API calls
- Store sensitive data securely (never in localStorage for tokens)

### Testing Requirements
- Write unit tests for all services and components
- Use Jasmine/Karma for testing
- Mock Supabase calls in tests
- Test error scenarios and edge cases
- Maintain minimum 70% code coverage

### Code Organization
- Keep components under 300 lines
- Extract reusable logic into services
- Create shared components for common UI elements
- Use enums for constants and magic strings
- Implement proper folder structure by feature
- Follow single responsibility principle

### Comments and Documentation
- Add JSDoc comments for public methods and complex logic
- Use TODO comments for future improvements
- Document component inputs/outputs with descriptions
- Include README files for complex features

### Git Practices
- Use conventional commits (feat:, fix:, refactor:, etc.)
- Keep commits atomic and focused
- Write descriptive commit messages

## Specific Project Rules

### ScentTwin Features
- **Onboarding**: Welcome screen → Goal selection → Designer/Niche preference → Selfie scan → Quiz → Owned bottles
- **Recommendation Engine**: A/B/C blind reveal with P/R/K scoring system
- **Privacy**: Selfie processing client-side only, data deletion on demand
- **Monetization**: Free tier limits after month one, Pro plan features

### API Endpoints
- `/recommend` - Returns anonymized A/B/C cards
- `/reveal` - Unlocks perfume names after tasks
- `/rating` - Stores user feedback
- `/best-price` - Fetches retailer offers

### Database Tables
- `user_profiles` - User settings and preferences
- `selfies_derived` - Seasonal subtype data only
- `perfumes` - Fragrance catalog
- `user_ratings` - Community feedback
- `wardrobes` - User collections
- `price_offers` - Retailer pricing

## Response Format

When generating code:
1. **Always create separate files** for .ts, .html, and .scss
2. Show complete file contents, not snippets
3. Include all necessary imports
4. Add proper TypeScript types and interfaces
5. Include error handling
6. Apply design system styles
7. Add comments for complex logic
8. Follow the file structure defined above

## Visual Priority

Remember: This app's success depends on its **eye-catching, premium UI**. Every component should feel polished, modern, and visually stunning. Use animations, gradients, glass-morphism, and the purple/gold color scheme consistently.

## Don't

- Never use inline templates or styles
- Never use `any` type
- Never skip error handling
- Never forget to unsubscribe from observables
- Never hardcode values (use constants/enums)
- Never skip accessibility attributes
- Never create NgModules for new features (use standalone)
- Never forget mobile responsiveness

## Do

- Always use separate .ts/.html/.scss files
- Always apply the design system
- Always include hover/active states
- Always add smooth transitions
- Always implement proper error handling
- Always use TypeScript strict mode
- Always test components before marking complete
- Always follow Angular best practices
- Always prioritize visual appeal and user experience
